		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=389495"><span id=Scholar>Nuanil</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br />30 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Nuanil&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Here's my reasons why PLing is wrong and bad for developing good players:<br><br><br><br>1. You're a crutch for them to lean on so they can take on stuff they should never think of taking on.&nbsp;&nbsp;And they don't learn a true sense of their capabilities.  It's almost never good enough to tell your toddler the iron is hot, cuz 9 times out of 10 they gotta touch to realize it hurts.  And people that haven't been forced to do it on their own a few times tend to expect too much per kill without taking the party makeup into account.<br><br>2. By limiting how much healing the whm's are able to do you gimp their healing skill stat, and it's hard enough to keep capped.  And it becomes incredibly boring for the healers because they feel useless, as a general rule.  <br><br>3. 10-25 is where you really learn how to play the job well, and for most if you don't get a good feel for the job in these 15 levels, then most people never will.  Having a power level throughout this region of levels allows the entire party to slack off, and just mash buttons while killing stuff, never being forced to learn the more advanced styles of play.<br><br>Powerleveling isn't as damaging to player skills if it's a babysitting role, waiting for things to go to hell before saving the day, but making the entire party work for their experience.<br><br>And as a thief I've had the displeasure of partying with people that were clearly powerlevled.  Tanks that refuse to stand still despite how often or nicely you ask then to stand still, samurai that don't know what a skillchain is let alone how to pull one off, and the inability of these morons to understand how to set up a proper SATA, despite only asking:<br><br>1. the tank to stand still<br>2. another melee to stand behind the mob<br><br>I often wonder if people are simply role playing the intelligence stat too literally when they play melee classes.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
